# 🔐 Broken Function Level Authorization (BFLA)

---

# 📌 Overview

BFLA occurs when:

- API does NOT enforce authorization
- Users access functions they shouldn't

👉 Example:

    Normal user → Access admin API

---

# ⚠️ Vulnerability Description

- Missing role checks
- Over-permissive endpoints
- Client-side authorization only

---

# 🔍 How BFLA Happens

1. No role validation  
2. Admin endpoints exposed  
3. Frontend-only restrictions  
4. Missing backend checks  

---

# 🔥 Real Vulnerable Endpoint

    DELETE /identity/api/v2/admin/videos/52

👉 Admin-only functionality

---

# 🧪 PoC

Request:

    DELETE /identity/api/v2/admin/videos/52
    Authorization: Bearer <USER_TOKEN>

JWT:

    {
      "role": "user"
    }

---

# 🚨 Issue

- User role = user
- Still able to access admin API

👉 No authorization check

---

# 💥 Impact

- Delete data
- Perform admin actions
- Full privilege escalation
- System compromise

---

# 📊 Severity

- HIGH

---

# 🔎 Indicators

Look for endpoints:

    /admin/
    /internal/
    /management/
    /superuser/

Signs:

- Works with normal user token
- No 403 response
- No role validation

---

# 🛡️ Remediation

---

## 1. Implement RBAC

    if user.role != "admin":
        return 403

---

## 2. Enforce Server-Side Authorization

❌ Never trust frontend

---

## 3. Restrict Admin Endpoints

    /admin/* → Admin only

---

## 4. Centralized Authorization Middleware

- Validate every request

---

## 5. Logging & Monitoring

- Track admin actions

---

# ✅ Secure Response Example

    HTTP/1.1 403 Forbidden

    {
      "error": "Unauthorized access"
    }

---

# 📊 Summary

| Issue | BFLA |
|------|------|
| Type | Authorization |
| Impact | Privilege Escalation |
| Severity | High |

